liked_videos.title: Deep Dive into LLMs like ChatGPT
liked_videos.description:
This is a general audience deep dive into the Large Language Model (LLM) AI technology that powers ChatGPT and related products. It is covers the full training stack of how the models are developed, along with mental models of how to think about their "psychology", and how to get the best use them in practical applications. I have one "Intro to LLMs" video already from ~year ago, but that is just a re-recording of a random talk, so I wanted to loop around and do a lot more comprehensive version.

Instructor
Andrej was a founding member at OpenAI (2015) and then Sr. Director of AI at Tesla (2017-2022), and is now a founder at Eureka Labs, which is building an AI-native school. His goal in this video is to raise knowledge and understanding of the state of the art in AI, and empower people to effectively use the latest and greatest in their work.
Find more at https://karpathy.ai/ and https://x.com/karpathy

Chapters
00:00:00 introduction
00:01:00 pretraining data (internet)
00:07:47 tokenization
00:14:27 neural network I/O
00:20:11 neural network internals
00:26:01 inference
00:31:09 GPT-2: training and inference
00:42:52 Llama 3.1 base model inference
00:59:23 pretraining to post-training
01:01:06 post-training data (conversations)
01:20:32 hallucinations, tool use, knowledge/working memory
01:41:46 knowledge of self
01:46:56 models need tokens to think
02:01:11 tokenization revisited: models struggle with spelling
02:04:53 jagged intelligence
02:07:28 supervised finetuning to reinforcement learning
02:14:42 reinforcement learning
02:27:47 DeepSeek-R1
02:42:07 AlphaGo
02:48:26 reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF)
03:09:39 preview of things to come
03:15:15 keeping track of LLMs
03:18:34 where to find LLMs
03:21:46 grand summary

liked_videos.title: Karpathy Vibe Coding Full Tutorial with Cursor (Zero Coding)
liked_videos.description:
Today we talked about the concept and execution of vibe coding, a method where you speak your coding ideas into existence using cutting‚Äêedge AI tools. We explored how to use Cursor Composer alongside Sonnet and WhisperFlow to generate, edit, and run code with minimal manual intervention. The tutorial guided viewers through setting up a project from a Next.js template, cloning a repository, and managing API keys through an .env file to maintain secure credentials. Additionally, the video detailed the process of building a ChatGPT clone using the latest OpenAI API, complete with real-time debugging and iterative improvements on design elements such as input fields, sidebars, and smooth text animations. The discussion also emphasized the importance of keeping the AI prompt context minimal for optimal performance, and it provided insights on how to save and upload projects to GitHub effortlessly. Finally, we touched on integrating real-time voice interaction using the 11Labs API to further enhance the coding experience and pay homage to AI pioneers like Karpathy

Footnotes

Perplexity Spaces (Just like Custom GPT's) Prompt:
i am making app in nextjs:
user is going to give input that they want to put in their site:
you're job is to find a method to do that:
describe what the api does, then output example code. then put a direct link to find the api key.

liked_videos.title: Guangzhou autonomous driving bus experience: My first time in a self-driving car
liked_videos.description:
Hello everyone! Today, I'm taking you on a tour to experience Guangzhou's driverless bus. Guangzhou has a total of four autonomous bus routes, and the one I'm taking you on today is a route that doesn't require any tickets or reservations. This self-driving bus has many advantages, such as being smooth, having a good view, and being very comfortable to ride. It's a great experience for those who get carsick.

I'll also take you on a tour of a route that runs through the city center. This route has a steering wheel and a safety driver, and it requires advance reservations, so it's a bit more complicated.

Finally, we'll visit a building on Guangzhou's Yuejiang West Road, which is a new business center that Guangzhou is focusing on developing. Many large companies will have offices here. This area also has an autonomous bus route.

The new developments have raised alarms on whether America‚Äôs global lead in artificial intelligence is shrinking and called into question big tech‚Äôs massive spend on building AI models and data centers. liked_videos.title: *YUMMIEST* COOKER BROWNIE RECIPE #shorts
liked_videos.description:
Episode 3 of #NoOvenNoProblem ‚òÄÔ∏è, a series where I make your favourite desserts at home WITHOUT an oven üíÅüèª‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏èMonsoon season calls for warm, chocolaty and fudgy Brownies and this version in a cooker has to be one of the easiest ways to enjoy these delights without much hassle üôåüèª‚ù§Ô∏è

Ingredients 
ü§åüèª1/2 cup butter (100g)
ü§åüèª1/4 cup dark chocolate (43g)
ü§åüèª6 tbsp jaggery
ü§åüèª3/4 cup milk, warm
ü§åüèª1/2 cup wholewheat flour
ü§åüèª6 tbsp cocoa powder
ü§åüèª1/3 cup milk chocolate chunks (58g)
ü§åüèªChocolate chips, for top

Method
1. Spread a layer of salt at the bottom of a cooker and set it in low to medium  heat. Place a hollow stand in the middle and cover the cooker with the lid, remove the whistle and let it preheat for 10 mins. 
2. Grease a 6 inch square pan with butter or oil and line it with parchment paper leaving handles on two ends for easy lifting after baking.
3. Add butter and chocolate in a bowl and melt it in a microwave at 30 seconds intervals till completely melted.
4. Add jaggery powder and milk to the above mixture and mix well. 
5. Dump in the flour and cocoa powder into this mixture and form a smooth lump-free batter. 
6. Fold in the milk chocolate chunks evenly into the batter and transfer the batter into the greased pan. Sprinkle some more chocolate chips on top of the batter.
7. Carefully place the brownie pan inside the cooker and bake for 25-30 mins. 
8. Let the brownies come at room temperature before demoulding and slicing. You can also refrigerate the brownies for 30 mins for sharper edges.

liked_videos.title: The art and science of happiness | Arthur Brooks | TEDxKC
liked_videos.description:
Harvard Professor of happiness, Arthur Brooks, turns the tables on the idea of the "bucket list" as a way of achieving satisfaction, showing us where real joy and contentment are far more likely to be found. Arthur C. Brooks is the William Henry Bloomberg Professor of the Practice of Public Leadership at the Harvard Kennedy School and Professor of Management Practice at the Harvard Business School.

Before joining the Harvard faculty in 2019, he served for 10 years as president of the Washington, D.C.-based American Enterprise Institute (AEI), one of the world‚Äôs leading think tanks. Under his leadership, the Institute more than doubled its annual revenues, deepened its outreach to leaders across the ideological spectrum and expanded its research portfolio to include work on poverty, happiness and human potential.

Brooks is the author of 12 books, including the #1 New York Times bestseller ‚ÄúFrom Strength to Strength.‚Äù He is also a columnist for The Atlantic and host of the podcast ‚ÄúHow to Build a Happy Life with Arthur Brooks.‚Äù Brooks gives more than 100 speeches per year around the U.S., Europe and Asia. This talk was given at a TEDx event using the TED conference format but independently organized by a local community. Learn more at https://www.ted.com/tedx

liked_videos.description:
üåç Have you ever wondered which country gets to celebrate the New Year first? The answer lies in how the Earth is divided into 24 time zones! ‚è∞ Because time moves from east to west, the first country to welcome the New Year is Kiribati üéâ an island nation located near the International Date Line. Its time zone is so unique, it even stretches the rules of geography! Meanwhile, the last place to ring in the New Year is American Samoa. üï∞Ô∏è These islands are surprisingly close to Kiribati but sit on the opposite side of the Date Line, creating an astonishing 25-hour time difference! üåê‚ú®

For those who don't know what a MicroSaaS is - think of it as a small, focused software product that solves a specific problem, for a niche group of people, usually run by one person or a tiny team.

In this video, I'm sharing my complete journey - from working a regular job to building my first MicroSaaS. This isn't one of those "get rich quick" videos. I'll break down the exact steps of How I built Supermeme.ai.

liked_videos.description:
Two branches. One tree. Check out the Karate Kid: Legends trailer for the upcoming movie starring Jackie Chan, Ben Wang, and Ralph Macchio. Karate Kid: Legends also stars Joshua Jackson, Sadie Stanley, and Ming-Na Wen.

In Karate Kid: Legends, after a family tragedy, kung fu prodigy Li Fong (Ben Wang) is uprooted from his home in Beijing and forced to move to New York City with his mother. Li struggles to let go of his past as he tries to fit in with his new classmates, and although he doesn't want to fight, trouble seems to find him everywhere. When a new friend needs his help, Li enters a karate competition ‚Äì but his skills alone aren't enough. Li's kung fu teacher Mr. Han (Jackie Chan) enlists original Karate Kid Daniel LaRusso (Ralph Macchio) for help, and Li learns a new way to fight, merging their two styles into one for the ultimate martial arts showdown.

Karate Kid: Legends is produced by Karen Rosenfelt. Jenny Hinkey and Ralph Macchio serve as executive producers. It is written by Rob Lieber.

Karate Kid: Legends, directed by Jonathan Entwistle, opens in theaters on May 30, 2025.

Ever wondered why planes flying over the Atlantic üåä seem to follow a narrow, invisible path? ‚úàÔ∏è It‚Äôs all thanks to the incredible Jet Stream Highway! üí®‚ú® This powerful, fast-moving air current helps guide planes across the ocean, making flights not only shorter ‚è±Ô∏è but also more efficient üí∏ and safer üõ°Ô∏è. Picture a constant stream of planes moving in perfect sync along this ‚Äòinvisible highway‚Äô - but how do they avoid collisions, especially with no radar coverage üì° in the middle of the Atlantic? üö¶‚úàÔ∏è Find out why flights from the USA üá∫üá∏ to Europe üá™üá∫ are typically faster thanks to this high-speed wind üå¨Ô∏è But there‚Äôs more - an intricate system called the North Atlantic Tracks üó∫Ô∏è functions like an air traffic map. Every day, experts analyze shifting jet streams and weather patterns to create these safe ‚Äòtracks‚Äô for planes to follow. Pilots request permission to join these paths based on altitude, speed, and distance, keeping every flight safe and efficient. From fuel savings ‚õΩ to increased speeds üí® these invisible highways are an impressive feat of coordination that keeps our skies organized and our trips smooth.

liked_videos.title: Why are CARS SO EXPENSIVE in India? | A Case Study | tbh
liked_videos.description:
In recent years, the cost of cars in India has been steadily rising, creating significant challenges for the middle class. What was once considered a luxury item has now become a near-essential mode of transportation, yet the affordability gap continues to widen. The increasing car prices can be attributed to several complex factors that impact the overall cost structure.

Taxation plays a crucial role in determining car prices in India. The government levies multiple taxes, including Goods and Services Tax (GST), road tax, registration charges, and additional state-specific levies. These taxes can add substantial amounts to the base price of a vehicle. For instance, the GST rates vary between 5% and 28% depending on the type and value of the car, significantly inflating the final price.
Manufacturing costs have also risen due to several factors. 

The implementation of stricter safety and emission norms requires manufacturers to invest in advanced technologies and more sophisticated manufacturing processes. Additionally, raw material costs, including steel, aluminum, and electronic components, have increased globally. The transition towards electric and hybrid vehicles has further pushed up development and production expenses.

Import duties on crucial components and the need for localization add another layer of complexity to pricing. While the government encourages domestic manufacturing through initiatives like Make in India, the automotive supply chain still faces challenges that contribute to higher costs.

The result is a challenging landscape for middle-class consumers, who find themselves stretching their budgets to own a vehicle that has become increasingly necessary for daily life in India's rapidly developing urban and suburban environments.

liked_videos.title: Can you save tax by transferring to Spouse's account? Housewife's tax implications
liked_videos.description:
Join Learner's Community : https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCmfl6VteCu880D8Txl4vEag/join
Official Website - Courses & Learning Materials : https://www.financeboosan.in  

Clubbing of Income Under Indian Tax Laws
Clubbing of Income refers to the inclusion of another person's income in the taxpayer's total income for tax computation purposes. This concept is aimed at preventing tax evasion by taxpayers who might otherwise transfer their income or assets to others, typically family members, to reduce their tax liability.

The provisions governing clubbing of income are outlined in Sections 60 to 64 of the Income Tax Act, 1961. Here‚Äôs an overview:

1. Transfer of Income without Transfer of Assets (Section 60)
If a person transfers income from an asset to another person without transferring the ownership of the asset, the income from such an asset is taxed in the hands of the transferor.
Example: If Mr. A owns a property and transfers the rental income to his spouse without transferring the property itself, the rental income will still be taxed in Mr. A's hands.

2. Revocable Transfer of Assets (Section 61)
If a person transfers an asset under a revocable arrangement, the income from such an asset will be taxed in the hands of the transferor.
A revocable transfer is one where the transferor retains the right to reclaim the asset or income.
Example: Mr. A transfers a property to his son but retains the right to revoke the transfer. In such a case, the income from the property is taxed in Mr. A's hands.

3. Income of Spouse (Section 64(1)(ii))
If an individual‚Äôs spouse earns income from an entity where the individual has substantial interest, and the spouse does not possess technical or professional qualifications, the income is clubbed with the income of the individual.
Substantial interest typically means holding at least 20% of the equity shares or profits in the entity.
Example: Mrs. A works in a company where Mr. A has a 30% shareholding. If Mrs. A has no technical or professional qualification for the job, her salary will be clubbed with Mr. A‚Äôs income.

4. Income from Assets Transferred to Spouse (Section 64(1)(iv))
Income from assets transferred directly or indirectly to the spouse without adequate consideration is clubbed with the income of the transferor, except where the asset is transferred under an agreement to live apart.
Example: If Mr. A gifts a house to Mrs. A, the rental income from the house will be taxed in Mr. A‚Äôs hands.

5. Income from Assets Transferred to Son‚Äôs Wife (Section 64(1)(vi))
If an individual transfers assets to their son's wife without adequate consideration, the income from such assets is clubbed with the income of the transferor.
Example: Mr. A gifts shares to his daughter-in-law. The dividend income from these shares will be taxed in Mr. A‚Äôs hands.

6. Income of Minor Child (Section 64(1A))
The income of a minor child is clubbed with the income of the parent whose total income (excluding the child‚Äôs income) is greater.
There are certain exceptions where the child‚Äôs income is not clubbed, such as income earned by a minor from manual work, or from an activity involving the minor‚Äôs talent, or income of a minor child suffering from a disability as specified under Section 80U.
The parent can claim an exemption of up to ‚Çπ1,500 per child per year on the income that is clubbed.

7. Implications of Clubbing of Income
Clubbing can lead to a higher tax liability since the income is added to the transferor‚Äôs total income.
The clubbed income is taxed at the transferor's applicable slab rate, which might be higher than that of the recipient.

8. Prevention of Misuse
The provisions are designed to prevent misuse, such as transferring assets or income to relatives in lower tax brackets to reduce the overall tax burden.
The tax authorities are vigilant in ensuring that these rules are not circumvented through artificial transactions.

Conclusion
The concept of clubbing of income plays a significant role in ensuring that tax liabilities are not reduced unfairly through the transfer of assets or income. It is important for taxpayers to understand these provisions to comply with tax laws and avoid penalties or additional taxes. Proper tax planning and consultation with a tax professional can help manage these aspects effectively.

liked_videos.title: Multi-cap funds: A smarter way to invest in mid and small caps?
liked_videos.description:
Mid-cap and small-cap funds are among the most sought-after mutual funds. However, their high volatility is a problem. In this video, we find out if multi-cap funds can be a better way to invest in mid and small caps. 

Multi-cap funds are required to invest at least 25% of their assets each in large, mid and small caps. So, at any point, they have 50% assets invested in mid and small caps. Their large-cap exposure helps provide the required stability. So, multi-cap funds can be both rewarding and less volatile.

Few other diversified categories provide this return mix. For example, flexi-cap funds tend to be large-cap heavy and large & mid-cap funds tend to be underweight in small caps. So, multi-cap funds are in a distinguished position.

But the analysis of multi-cap funds is not easy as they came into being only in 2021. They have an interesting history that you can learn more about in the video. So, to analyse these funds, we had to create a multi-cap fund. We did so by taking the Nifty 100, Nifty Midcap 150 and Nifty Smallcap 250 total-return indices and then allocating assets to them as per the asset allocation of multi-cap funds over the last 2 years. We also rebalanced the resulting proxy multi-cap fund on a yearly basis.

We then compared the performance of this proxy multi-cap fund with the mid-cap and small-cap indices. The comparison revealed that not only did the proxy multi-cap fund do considerably well on the returns front but it also offered less volatility and better downside protection. 

Though the study had its limitations, it can be concluded that multi-cap funds can be a good way to invest in mid and small caps. Plus, they can also take care of asset allocation across market caps.

liked_videos.title: Surviving Market Meltdowns: Key Lessons from the Sensex Falls | Dhirendra Kumar Shares Expert Advice
liked_videos.description:
In this episode of Investors' Hangout, Dhirendra Kumar, an expert in mutual funds and market strategies, explains how to navigate market meltdowns and turn them into opportunities.¬†
From understanding market cycles to aligning your investment goals and practising asset allocation, Dhirendra provides invaluable advice on surviving and thriving during periods of market volatility. He discusses the importance of long-term investing, why some sectors are hit harder during downturns, and how asset allocation can balance risk and reward. Learn how to stay calm and make informed decisions to emerge stronger after a market fall.

Chapters:
00:04 Introduction
00:28 What key strategies can investors use to stay calm and avoid panic selling during a market meltdown?
02:57 What do historical Sensex recoveries teach us about timing the market, and why is staying invested critical for long-term success?
04:35 How can investors balance risk and opportunity during a downturn, and what role should asset allocation play in surviving market volatility?
06:13 Viewer's Question - If all funds are doing well (3 to 5-star-rated), how does having too many funds translate into a higher expense ratio and lower returns?
09:13 Closing
09:23 Key Takeaways:
- Align with Long-Term Goals: Invest in equities for the long run, not for short-term needs.
- Avoid Daily Monitoring: Don't obsess over daily market movements; focus on the long term.
- Understand Market Cycles: Markets recover over time, so stay patient during downturns.
- Use Asset Allocation: Balance risk by diversifying between equities and fixed income.
- Choose the Right Fund: Start with a balanced or hybrid fund for stability, not speculative ones.

liked_videos.title: Masterclass on Wealth Creation with Mutual Funds: Dhirendra Kumar's Ultimate Guide for New Investors
liked_videos.description:
Welcome to the 300th episode of Investors' Hangout! In this special masterclass, Dhirendra Kumar, CEO of Value Research, delivers a powerful session on building wealth with mutual funds. If you're a young investor or someone new to the world of finance, this episode is packed with timeless insights and practical advice on creating long-term wealth through smart, disciplined investing.

Dhirendra Kumar covers:
- Why simplicity beats complexity in investing
- The critical role of starting early and forming good financial habits
- How to beat inflation and grow your wealth with equity investments
- The importance of asset allocation and tax planning
- Common investing mistakes to avoid and the value of patience

This masterclass also includes a lively Q&A session with young professionals where Dhirendra answers real-life questions on everything from balancing debt and investments to choosing funds for different financial goals. Whether you're a beginner or looking to refine your strategy, this episode offers clear guidance to help you navigate the world of mutual funds and build a secure financial future.

Chapters:
00:04 Introduction
00:21 Masterclass with Dhirendra Kumar - Wealth Creation with Mutual Funds
13:21 Q&A
37:59 Close

Don‚Äôt miss out on this chance to learn from one of India's top financial experts! Watch now to kickstart your wealth creation journey with confidence.

Key Takeaways:
- Start Early, Form Good Habits: Begin investing small amounts as soon as possible; early habits build lifelong wealth.
- Beat Inflation with Equity: Investing in equity helps you outpace inflation and build real value over the long term.
- Keep It Simple: Avoid complex products and focus on core elements‚Äîemergency fund, essential insurance, and a few good mutual funds.
- Practice Asset Allocation: Diversify across assets as your portfolio grows to reduce risk and stabilise returns.
- Patience is Key: Wealth building isn‚Äôt about chasing quick gains. It's about disciplined investing, even during market volatility.

liked_videos.title: How China Uses Mexico To Avoid U.S. Tariffs
liked_videos.description:
For the first time in more than two decades Mexico overtook China as the largest importer of goods to the U.S.

Mexican goods imported to the U.S. totaled $475 billion in 2023 about $20 billion higher than the previous year. Feuling that trend are simmering trade tensions between Beijing and Washington, an effort to bring U.S. imports closer to home and a burgeoning Mexican manufacturing base. But there‚Äôs another factor at play. To avoid American tariffs Chinese companies are using Mexico as a backdoor to the U.S. So how is China able to circumvent U.S. tariffs and what are logistic companies doing to prepare for the upcoming boom in Mexican trade. CNBC traveled to Mexico City and El Paso to find out.

Chapters:
0:00 - 3:05 Introduction
3:06 - 6:55 Chapter 1 Evading U.S. tariffs 
6:56 - 10:51 Chapter 2 Mexico's manufacturing boom
10:52 - 13:55 Chapter 3 Policing the border 
13:56 - 16:06 Chapter 4 Bringing goods to the U.S.  
16:07 - 19:08 Chapter 5 Maersk, DHL and Uber Freight

liked_videos.title: Swiggy‚Äôs IPO makes 500 employees crorepatis, 9 executives to gain over Rs 50 cr
liked_videos.description:
Food delivery giant Swiggy‚Äôs initial public offering (IPO) is set to make 500 of its employees crorepatis through employee stock options (ESOPs). The Bengaluru-based food and commodities aggregator listed at 7.7% premium of Rs 420 on the National Stock Exchange today. The company has a total of 231 million outstanding ESOPs, valued at over Rs 9,000 crore, the company said in its DRHP report. A total of 5,000 employees are set to benefit from the ESOP payout. Swiggy‚Äôs ESOP payout is set to top that of Walmart-backed e-commerce company Flipkart, which had a $1.5 billion payout.
Swiggy's founders and top management were allocated ESOPs worth Rs 2,600 crore in its latest stock ownership plan

liked_videos.description:
Former U.S. President and Republican Donald Trump made a comeback as he won a second term in office, defeating Vice-President Kamala Harris, the Democratic nominee, to become the 47th President of the United States. 

‚Äú‚Ä¶We‚Äôre going to help our country heal,‚Äù Mr. Trump said, speaking in West Palm Breach, Florida, before he had reached the 270 mark. Mr. Trump spoke of the coming of a ‚Äúgolden age‚Äù for America, saying, ‚ÄúAmerica has given us an unprecedented and powerful mandate. We have taken back control of the Senate.‚Äù

In her concession speech on Wednesday at Howard University, her alma mater, Kamala Harris said, ‚ÄúWe must accept the results of this election.‚Äù She encouraged supporters to continue fighting for their vision of the country after her loss to Donald Trump. The Democratic vice president said the battle would continue ‚Äúin the voting booth, in the courts and in the public square.‚Äù

‚ÄúWhile I concede this election, I do not concede the fight that fueled this campaign,‚Äù Harris said.

liked_videos.title: Top 5 Index Funds in India to Buy & Hold Forever
liked_videos.description:
Subscribe for more: https://www.youtube.com/@remoterish?sub_confirmation=1

In this video, I challenge the popular concept of forever buying and holding mutual funds. 

While many investors follow this advice, I believe it's unrealistic. 

Every year, you see a new list of top mutual funds across large-cap, mid-cap, flexi-cap, and more. If the list keeps changing, how can anyone expect to buy and hold a fund forever?

I explain why mutual funds constantly evolve, with fund managers changing, strategies shifting, and market cycles turning. 

Over time, these factors can dramatically affect your returns. In contrast, index funds provide a much more stable option for long-term investing. 

With index funds, the role of the fund manager is minimal, and the portfolio simply tracks the top companies in the market, making them more reliable for holding over the long term. 

There's no need to worry about constant shifts in performance or new funds entering the spotlight every year.

I explore why index funds are easier to hold forever, how they minimize the emotional and strategic noise that comes from market speculation, and why this approach works better for long-term wealth building. 

I also touch on why it's crucial to avoid being swayed by flashy marketing from mutual funds, which often promise high returns but require constant attention and changes to your strategy.

If you're someone who's aiming to build a long-term portfolio with minimal intervention and wants to stay focused on the core principles of compounding, this video will give you a practical guide on how to achieve that through index investing.

Key Takeaways:
The myth of holding mutual funds forever.
How index funds offer simplicity and stability.
Why market noise from fund managers can disrupt long-term plans.
The power of sticking with funds that change the least.

liked_videos.title: How China is designing flood-resistant cities
liked_videos.description:
These "sponge city" designs resist floods and increase biodiversity to help us adapt to a changing climate.

This episode is presented by Delta. Delta doesn‚Äôt have a say in our editorial decisions, but they make videos like this possible. For more information, visit http://www.delta.com/sustainability.

Subscribe to our channel and turn on notifications (üîî) so you don't miss any videos: http://goo.gl/0bsAjO

From rising sea levels in Mumbai to unbearable heat in Houston, cities around the world are feeling the effects of climate change. Unfortunately, they don‚Äôt always have the right infrastructure to handle its impacts ‚Äî which is one reason why cities are beginning to reimagine urban design. One of these designs is a ‚Äúsponge city.‚Äù

Although one city design certainly won‚Äôt save us from the effects of climate change, ‚Äúsponge cities‚Äù can help with how we live with it. 

Here are some studies and articles we used to inform our reporting:

Biodiversity ‚Äî our strongest natural defense against climate change: https://www.un.org/en/climatechange/science/climate-issues/biodiversity

Sponge City, Shenzhen Explores the Benefits of Designing with Nature: https://www.lincolninst.edu/publications/articles/sponge-city-shenzhen-explores-benefits-designing-with-nature

Sponge City Practices in China: From Pilot Exploration to Systemic Demonstration: https://www.mdpi.com/2073-4441/14/10/1531

The ocean is rising ‚Äî and so is Miami‚Äôs skyline: https://www.vox.com/climate/23872640/coastal-climate-ocean-rising-miami-florida-building

Sponge Cities: Integrating Green and Gray Infrastructure to Build Climate Change Resilience in the People‚Äôs Republic of China: https://www.adb.org/sites/default/files/publication/838386/adb-brief-222-sponge-cities-prc.pdf

How Is Climate Change Affecting Floods?: https://www.nytimes.com/article/flooding-climate-change.html

liked_videos.title: Stop Buying On Every Dip | The Right SIP Plus Lump Sum Strategy
liked_videos.description:
A lot of smart investors use the SIP-plus-lump sum strategy for better returns. They maintain an ongoing SIP in mutual funds, and when markets fall, they invest a lump sum amount to benefit from market corrections. Recently, on 4th June, we saw markets fall close to 6% following unexpected election results. On that day, many investors seized the opportunity to invest lump sums, aiming to capitalize on the correction.

But does this strategy work? In this video, we dive deep into the data to find surprising answers. We'll explore three key aspects: the type of correction (whether to invest when markets fall or when valuations are low), the size of the correction (ideal investment points at 5%, 10%, or 15% drops), and the optimal investment horizon to maximize returns with this strategy. Watch the video to discover which combination of variables produces the highest returns and how you can optimize your investment strategy.

liked_videos.title: How Amazon Failed to Understand India? - Business Case Study
liked_videos.description:
00:00 - Intro
02:00 - Arrival in India
03:21 - Strategy in India
06:16 - How is it Failing?
12:05 - Future of Amazon

Amazon's journey in India has been marked by both promise and challenges. In 2015, Jeff Bezos declared India as Amazon‚Äôs most crucial market after the US. India, with its rapid economic growth and emerging e-commerce landscape, appeared to be a perfect opportunity for Amazon to extend its global dominance. Initially, Amazon invested heavily, pouring over $5 billion into its operations, and significantly shaping the country‚Äôs e-commerce sector alongside Flipkart. Amazon's infrastructure, customer experience, and seller services helped the company gain a strong foothold, especially in tier-1 cities, positioning it as a major player in India's e-commerce landscape.

However, in recent years, Amazon's growth in India has slowed, and it is facing significant competition from newer players like Meesho, Zepto, and Blinkit. In FY-23, Amazon India‚Äôs revenue grew by only 3.4%, the slowest growth in its history. One of the primary reasons for this slowdown is the shift in India‚Äôs e-commerce landscape. India is not a homogenous market but is divided into different segments based on income and consumption patterns, often referred to as India 1, India 2, and India 3. Amazon initially targeted the premium segment, India 1, which accounted for a small portion of the population but the majority of the country's consumption. However, by 2017, this segment started reaching saturation, and the growth in e-commerce began shifting towards tier-2 and tier-3 cities (India 2 and 3), which have different needs and behaviors.

The arrival of Reliance Jio and the subsequent rise of internet penetration brought millions of new consumers from smaller towns online. These consumers, however, were more price-sensitive and less familiar with online shopping, and Amazon failed to adapt quickly to their needs. Meesho capitalized on this gap by introducing innovative solutions, such as selling through WhatsApp groups and enabling local resellers, which built trust and made online shopping accessible for this new wave of customers. Meesho‚Äôs zero-commission model and faster payment cycles for sellers also gave it a competitive advantage, especially among smaller sellers.

Another challenge for Amazon is the rise of quick commerce in India. Post-pandemic, companies like Blinkit revolutionized the market by offering 10-minute grocery and product deliveries. This sector, which didn‚Äôt exist a few years ago, is growing at an explosive rate, with Blinkit already being valued at $13 billion‚Äîhalf of Amazon India's valuation. While Amazon has always prided itself on fast delivery, it has yet to make significant moves into the quick commerce space, leaving it vulnerable to competitors.

Furthermore, government regulations have added to Amazon's difficulties. India‚Äôs regulatory environment is increasingly cautious of foreign dominance in crucial sectors like e-commerce. In 2019, new rules prevented companies like Amazon from selling products from brands in which they held a stake, forcing Amazon to remove hundreds of thousands of products from its platform. The Indian government‚Äôs push for a more open and competitive e-commerce sector, through initiatives like ONDC, also threatens Amazon's future in the country.

In response to these challenges, Amazon is now shifting focus to other sectors, such as cloud computing and digital payments. However, Amazon‚Äôs core e-commerce business remains essential to its overall strategy, as it serves as the distribution network for its other ventures. If the company cannot regain its momentum in e-commerce, its ability to expand into new areas may also be hampered. Despite the setbacks, the future of Amazon in India remains uncertain, and it will need to rethink its approach to compete in this rapidly changing market.

liked_videos.title: AI tools for software engineers, but without the hype ‚Äì with Simon Willison (Co-Creator of Django)
liked_videos.description:
On the first episode of the Pragmatic Engineer Podcast, I am joined by Simon Willison. Simon is one of the best-known software engineers experimenting with LLMs to boost his own productivity: he‚Äôs been doing this for more than three years, blogging about it in the open.

Simon is the creator of Datasette, an open-source tool for exploring and publishing data. He works full-time developing open-source tools for data journalism, centered on Datasette and SQLite. Previously, he was an engineering director at Eventbrite, joining through the acquisition of Lanyrd, a Y Combinator startup he co-founded in 2010. Simon is also a co-creator of the Django Web Framework. He has been blogging about web development since the early 2000s.

In today‚Äôs conversation, we dive deep into the realm of Gen AI and talk about the following: 

‚Ä¢ Simon‚Äôs initial experiments with LLMs and coding tools
‚Ä¢ Why fine-tuning is generally a waste of time‚Äîand when it‚Äôs not
‚Ä¢ RAG: an overview
‚Ä¢ Interacting with GPTs voice mode
‚Ä¢ Simon‚Äôs day-to-day LLM stack
‚Ä¢ Common misconceptions about LLMs and ethical gray areas 
‚Ä¢ How Simon‚Äôs productivity has increased and his generally optimistic view on these tools
‚Ä¢ Tips, tricks, and hacks for interacting with GenAI tools
‚Ä¢ And more! 

‚Äî

Brought to you by:
‚Ä¢ Codeium: ‚Äã‚ÄãJoin the 700K+ developers using the IT-approved AI-powered code assistant https://codeium.com/?utm_campaign=pragmatic
‚Ä¢ TLDR: Keep up with tech in 5 minutes https://tldr.tech/

Where to find Simon Willison:
‚Ä¢ X: https://x.com/simonw
‚Ä¢ LinkedIn: https://www.linkedin.com/in/simonwillison/
‚Ä¢ Website: https://simonwillison.net/
‚Ä¢ Mastodon: https://fedi.simonwillison.net/@simon

Where to find Gergely:
‚Ä¢ Newsletter: https://www.pragmaticengineer.com/
‚Ä¢ LinkedIn: https://www.linkedin.com/in/gergelyorosz/
‚Ä¢ X: https://x.com/GergelyOrosz

In this episode, we cover:
(02:15) Welcome
(05:28) Simon‚Äôs ‚Äòscary‚Äô experience with ChatGPT
(10:58) Simon‚Äôs initial experiments with LLMs and coding tools
(12:21) The languages that LLMs excel at
(14:50) To start LLMs by understanding the theory, or by playing around?
(16:35) Fine-tuning: what it is, and why it‚Äôs mostly a waste of time
(18:03) Where fine-tuning works
(18:31) RAG: an explanation
(21:34) The expense of running testing on AI
(23:15) Simon‚Äôs current AI stack 
(29:55) Common misconceptions about using LLM tools
(30:09) Simon‚Äôs stack ‚Äì continued 
(32:51) Learnings from running local models
(33:56) The impact of Firebug and the introduction of open-source 
(39:42) How Simon‚Äôs productivity has increased using LLM tools
(41:55) Why most people should limit themselves to 3-4 programming languages
(45:18) Addressing ethical issues and resistance to using generative AI
(49:11) Are LLMs are plateauing? Is AGI overhyped?
(55:45) Coding vs. professional coding, looking ahead
(57:27) The importance of systems thinking for software engineers 
(1:01:00) Simon‚Äôs advice for experienced engineers
(1:06:29) Rapid-fire questions
(1:09:26) Takeaways

The Pragmatic Engineer deepdives mentioned in this episode:
‚Ä¢ Applied AI software engineering: RAG https://newsletter.pragmaticengineer.com/p/rag 
‚Ä¢ AI tooling for software engineers: reality check https://newsletter.pragmaticengineer.com/p/ai-tooling-2024 

See the transcript and other references during the episode at https://newsletter.pragmaticengineer.com/p/ai-tools-for-software-engineers-simon-willison

liked_videos.title: RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation): the "Hello World" of AI applications
liked_videos.description:
RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation) is the "Hello World" of AI applications. Here's Simon Willison (the co-creator of Django and open source developer) sharing an interesting take in The Pragmatic Engineer Podcast on how easy it is to get started building one, and why it's so hard to build a really good one.

liked_videos.title: Welcome to the Hollywood Reporter India
liked_videos.description:
The Hollywood Reporter India, the first media outlet covering India's entertainment industry across regions and languages, is the premier and most trusted resource for interviews, reviews, videos, and more. Here is our mission statement from our editor by Anupama Chopra. 

With over 1,800 titles produced annually across more than 20 languages, India stands as the largest film producer globally. THR India aims to showcase the unique aesthetics, star systems, and cultural nuances of multiple thriving film industries across the country. Beyond cinema, the platform will cover India's booming streaming sector, its rapidly growing gaming market, and the explosive online content creation industry.

Brought to you by the RP Sanjiv Goenka Group, THR India leverages the 94-year legacy of the American brand to deliver insightful, informative, and credible entertainment journalism. From breaking news and trends to in-depth interviews and reviews, THR India promises to be the go-to source for all things entertainment across the Indian subcontinent.

liked_videos.title: Off Script with The Hollywood Reporter India | Filmmakers Roundtable
liked_videos.description:
In a never-before seen interaction, join THR India editor Anupama Chopra as she sits down with five visionary directors from across India for an insightful roundtable discussion on the first episode of Off Script with THR, India. This star-studded panel features the incomparable Vetri Maaran and Pa. Ranjith from Tamil cinema, game-changers Karan Johar and Zoya Akhtar from Hindi cinema, and the multifaceted Mahesh Narayanan from Malayalam cinema.

In this engaging conversation, the directors delve into the current state of Indian cinema, discussing everything from the challenges of the theatrical business to the evolving landscape of streaming platforms. They share personal insights into their creative processes, favorite aspects of filmmaking, and the unique challenges they face in their respective industries.

The discussion touches on crucial topics such as the Hema committee report, representation of caste violence in cinema, the willingness of big stars to take on challenging roles and the importance of maintaining artistic integrity while navigating commercial pressures. This roundtable offers a rare glimpse into the minds of some of India's most influential filmmakers, showcasing their passion, creativity, and dedication to their craft.

liked_videos.title: This is how your JOB will make you rich.
liked_videos.description:
We often see people on the internet labelling the 9-5 job as "modern slavery." But is that really the case?

It's widely believed that the modern 9-5 job comes with numerous problems ‚Äî long working hours, low wages, job insecurity, and office politics. Given all these issues, many think, "If I'm so skilled, why not just start something on my own?" And of course, the biggest question remains: Can a 9-5 job truly make you rich?

But is all of this actually true? Are our expectations from a 9-5 job valid, or are they shaped by the unrealistic narratives the internet often sells us?

Don‚Äôt worry, we‚Äôre here to de-influence the concept of jobs for you.

We hope you enjoy the video and leave with a more rational perspective. Let us know your thoughts and show some love in the comments below!

liked_videos.title: How Namma Yatri Ended Ola and Uber's Dominance?
liked_videos.description:
The video discusses the challenges faced by drivers working for cab-hailing services like Ola and Uber in India, particularly regarding commissions and delayed payments. It talks about a new business model introduced by Namma Yatri, a part of the government-led ONDC, aimed at addressing these issues. This model eliminates commissions and instead charges drivers a fixed subscription fee, offering them more control over their earnings and immediate payment from customers. Since its launch, this model has gained significant traction, with over 3 lakh drivers joining Namma Yatri, leading to its expansion into other cities.

The success of Namma Yatri's zero-commission model has put pressure on traditional players like Ola and Uber to adopt similar strategies. Rapido, another cab-hailing service, was the first to adopt this model, prompting Ola and Uber to follow suit to avoid losing drivers to competitors. This shift signifies a significant disruption in the cab-hailing industry, challenging the dominance of Ola and Uber and potentially reshaping the market dynamics.

Furthermore, Namma Yatri has announced plans to enter the cab-hailing business in Bengaluru, further intensifying competition in the sector. This move poses a significant threat to Ola and Uber, which have established themselves over the years. Ola, in particular, is gearing up for an IPO, adding more pressure on the company to adapt to changing market trends.

liked_videos.description:
Sanjeev Bikhchandani is the founder of InfoEdge and has been one of the boldest investors in the Indian Startup Ecosystem. 

Sanjeev first invested in Zomato back in 2010 and has since put in around 17.5 Million dollars. That money is now worth 3.7 Billion dollars, a staggering 217x return on investment. 

Sanjeev‚Äôs other successful bet was in PolicyBazaar, a company he has backed since 2007. His investment in the company of 69 Million dollars, is now worth 1.02 Billion dollars. 

But the question is, how did he achieve this?

In one word, the answer is ‚Äòpatience‚Äô. See, a typical VC firm has a fund cycle of 10 years, which means they have to exit before that. 

But the Indian market takes longer periods to give big returns, almost 15 years in these two cases.

And because of this reason, other VC firms like Sequoia and Softbank exited Zomato soon after its IPO and couldn‚Äôt make big returns.

liked_videos.title: Tutorials 2-Building Multi AI Agents Chatbots With External Tools With LangGraph
liked_videos.description:
LangGraph is a library for building stateful, multi-actor applications with LLMs, used to create agent and multi-agent workflows. Compared to other LLM frameworks, it offers these core benefits: cycles, controllability, and persistence. LangGraph allows you to define flows that involve cycles, essential for most agentic architectures, differentiating it from DAG-based solutions. As a very low-level framework, it provides fine-grained control over both the flow and state of your application, crucial for creating reliable agents. Additionally, LangGraph includes built-in persistence, enabling advanced human-in-the-loop and memory features.
Code Link: https://colab.research.google.com/drive/1S9Hvp6XrJ_Jy_vWt1MBXKnOvfxS9Z4oE?usp=sharing

liked_videos.title: What do tech pioneers think about the AI revolution? - BBC World Service
liked_videos.description:
Three leading engineers discuss the impact of the AI revolution.

Click here to subscribe to our channel üëâüèΩ https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

Intelligent machines are remaking our world. The speed of their improvement is accelerating fast and every day there are more things they can do better than us. There are risks, but the opportunities for human society are enormous. 

Three engineers at the forefront of that revolution come to London to join Caroline Steel and a public audience at the Great Hall of Imperial College.

Regina Barzilay from MIT created a major breakthrough in detecting early stage breast cancer. She also led the team that used machine learning to discover Halicin, the first new antibiotic in 30 years. 

David Silver is Principal Research Scientist at Google DeepMind. He led the AlphaGo team that built the AI to defeat the world‚Äôs best human player of Go. 

Paolo Pirjanian founded Embodied, and is a pioneer in developing emotionally intelligent robots to aid child development. 

Producer: Charlie Taylor

liked_videos.title: Inside Adani: Bloomberg TV Special | The Four Men Set to Inherit the $213 Billion Adani Empire
liked_videos.description:
India's $213 billion conglomerate Adani Group is recovering from a short seller attack that wiped out $150 billion from its market cap in 2023, before erasing losses. Now, its 62-year-old founder, billionaire Gautam Adani, tells Bloomberg he wants to retire in the next eight to 10 years. In the span of a couple of decades, he has taken the group from a small coal trading firm to a behemoth that controls large chunks of the infrastructure that help power India's $4 trillion economy. In a series of exclusive interviews with Bloomberg's Anto Antony, his handpicked successors reveal their plans for green energy, real estate and global expansion ‚Äî though with a more dialed-back risk appetite compared to the founder.

liked_videos.description:
From Apple and Goldman Sachs to Bilt and Wells Fargo, high-profile credit card partnership missteps reveal how risky these deals between brands and banks can be. Almost 30% of adults own co-branded credit cards as customers can earn different rewards like discounts or free hotel points. So why are some partnerships hitting road blocks?

WSJ explains how these complex partnerships work and what‚Äôs at stake.

liked_videos.description:
Global Stock Market Crash: Indian Markets Dip Amid US Recession Fears | Vantage with Palki Sharma

On August 5, the stock markets crashed nearly 3%, with banking, IT, metal, and oil & gas shares facing across-the-board selling. This global equity rout wiped out billions of dollars' worth of investor money in a single day. The sell-off was likely triggered by recession fears in the US, tensions in West Asia, and tepid quarterly results from India Inc. The Indian rupee touched an all-time low as well. Global markets - from Japan to South Korea, Europe and the US reported losses as well. Palki Sharma decodes the trends.

liked_videos.title: AI's trillion dollar time bomb
liked_videos.description:
There‚Äôs a time bomb ticking in the AI space: spending is too high, and returns are too low. Megacaps like Meta, Google and Amazon have seen capex spending surge as they throw cash at building out the infrastructure to stay ahead of the AI game. Microsoft in particular has spent billions at a premium valuation, and shelled out $13 billion investing in OpenAI while Apple was reportedly able to secure a partnership with the startup darling for free just 18 months later. That could be a warning for the broader AI space, as experts sound the alarm on the widening gap between what companies are spending on AI, and what they‚Äôre getting back from it. 

Chapters:
0:00 - AI‚Äôs trillion dollar time bomb
1:01 - Irrational exuberance 
5:51 - The trough of disillusionment 

Written and produced by: Jasmine Wu, Laura Batchelor & Deirdre Bosa

liked_videos.title: Vector Database: A Must-Know Guide
liked_videos.description:
This must-know guide will provide you with all the information you need to understand vector databases and how they are used in generative AI like LLM.

Unlike traditional databases, vector databases excel in identifying similarities between data objects, making them indispensable for tasks like movie recommendations and AI-driven insights.

What You'll Learn:

1. Understanding Traditional Databases: Learn how SQL databases organize data in rows and columns, and their limitations with fuzzy queries.
2. Introduction to Vector Databases: Discover how data is represented as multi-dimensional vectors, capturing the essence of text, images, and more.
3. Indexing and Querying: See how vector databases convert data into vectors for efficient storage and retrieval, using algorithms like word embeddings.
4. Real-World Applications: Explore a practical example of recommending movies using vector similarities.
5. Advanced Concepts: Delve into vector storage, indexing algorithms, distance metrics, and query processing engines.
6. Future of AI with RAG: Understand how vector databases enhance Retrieval Augmented Generation (RAG) for contextually relevant AI responses.

liked_videos.title: Why the US has so many tornadoes
liked_videos.description:
Tornado Alley experiences more tornadoes than anywhere else in the world ‚Äî why?
This video is presented by CuriosityStream: https://www.curiositystream.com/Vox

Become a Video Lab member! http://bit.ly/video-lab

The United States experiences more tornadoes than any other country, averaging over 1,200 per year. Most of those twisters are touching down in the central part of the country in an area called ‚ÄúTornado Alley.‚Äù While the boundaries of this tornado hotbed are disputed, there‚Äôs no denying that something is going on here ‚Äî and it all has to do with geography. 

The map we use in this video for Tornado Alley boundaries is from NOAA ‚Äî you can find that and more information on their website: https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/climate-information/extreme-events/us-tornado-climatology/tornado-alley

Information on tornado averages and trends can also be found at NOAA:
https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/climate-information/extreme-events/us-tornado-climatology/trends

You may have noticed on our graphic around the one-minute mark that many of the Southeastern US states are prone to tornadoes as well. This is because they‚Äôre part of an area called ‚ÄúDixie Alley.‚Äù The main difference between this area and Tornado Alley that tornadoes in Dixie Alley are more likely to touch down in the fall, while Tornado Alley experiences twisters in the early spring. This happens for the reasons outlined in the video above. This article offers a fairly compelling comparison of the two: 
http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.660.5241&rep=rep1&type=pdf

Finally, this video offered a simplified explanation of a really complex weather phenomenon. This National Geographic article does a really great job breaking it down again and also offers information on why it‚Äôs so hard to track and predict tornadoes:
https://news.nationalgeographic.com/2015/05/150511-tornadoes-storms-midwest-weather-science/

liked_videos.description:
Let's Ride. 
#TwistersMovie is only in theaters July 19.
_____ 
 
This summer, the epic studio disaster movie returns with an adrenaline-pumping, big-screen thrill ride that puts you in direct contact with one of nature‚Äôs most wondrous‚Äîand destructive‚Äîforces. 
 
From the producers of the Jurassic, Bourne and Indiana Jones series comes Twisters, 
a current-day chapter of the 1996 blockbuster, Twister. Directed by Lee Isaac Chung, the Oscar¬Æ nominated writer-director of Minari, Twisters stars Daisy Edgar-Jones (Where the Crawdads Sing), Glen Powell (Top Gun: Maverick) and Anthony Ramos (Transformers: Rise of the Beasts) as equal forces, with opposing motivations, who come together to try to predict, and possibly tame, the immense power of tornadoes.

Edgar-Jones stars as Kate Carter, a former storm chaser haunted by a devastating encounter with a tornado during her college years who now studies storm patterns on screens safely in New York City. She is lured back to the open plains by her friend, Javi (Ramos) to test a groundbreaking new tracking system. There, she crosses paths with Tyler Owens (Powell), the charming and reckless social-media superstar who thrives on posting his storm-chasing adventures with his raucous crew, the more dangerous the better.
 
As storm season intensifies, terrifying phenomena never seen before are unleashed, and Kate, Tyler, Javi and their crews find themselves squarely in the paths of multiple storm systems converging over central Oklahoma in the fight of their lives.

Twisters features an exciting new cast, including Nope‚Äôs Brandon Perea, Golden Globe winner Maura Tierney (Beautiful Boy), Sasha Lane (American Honey), Harry Hadden-Paton (The Crown), David Corenswet (We Own This City), Daryl McCormack (Peaky Blinders), Tunde Adebimpe (Leave the World Behind), Katy O‚ÄôBrian (Ant-Man and the Wasp: Quantumania), Nik Dodani (Atypical), Kiernan Shipka (Chilling Adventures of Sabrina) and Paul Scheer (Black Monday).

From Amblin, Twisters is directed by Lee Isaac Chung and is produced by Oscar¬Æ nominee Frank Marshall (Jurassic and Indiana Jones franchises) and by Patrick Crowley (Jurassic and Bourne franchises). The screenplay is by Mark L. Smith, writer of the Best Picture nominee The Revenant, from a story by Joseph Kosinski (Oblivion), based on characters created by Michael Crichton & Anne Marie Crichton. The executive producers are Academy Award¬Æ winner Steven Spielberg, Thomas Hayslip and Ashley Jay Sandberg. Twisters will be distributed by Universal Pictures domestically and by Warner Bros. Pictures internationally.

liked_videos.title: Watch this before selling your mutual funds | Money Psychology
liked_videos.description:
If you're an investor who does a lot of research before picking stocks or mutual funds for your portfolio, you've probably counted on the magic of compounding over the long term. But, can you accurately predict when to exit your mutual funds? The answer is yes!

There are tons of videos out there about how to buy the best mutual funds for your portfolio, but very few talk about when to sell them. The truth is, you can only truly benefit from compounding if you know the right time to sell your mutual funds.

In this video, we'll cover the good and bad reasons people sell their mutual funds and talk about SWP (Systematic Withdrawal Plan) and its usefulness in goal based investing. Also, check out the resources below. 

Do show us your love in the comments below!

At the age 61, Keir Starmer is the oldest person to become UK's new Prime Minister in almost half a century, but was only elected to parliament nine years ago. The married father-of-two is unlike most modern politicians: he had a long and distinguished career before becoming an MP and his views are rooted in pragmatism rather than ideology. üá∫üá∏ Energy Crisis of USA
Someone said there is no power cut in the USA üá∫üá∏ What a joke. 
USA's Power Grid is so old. A 98-year-old hook had caused a wildfire. 
Utility companies like P&GE are going bankrupt trying to fix their equipment. 
The whole country is struggling to meet the energy requirements. 
With more electric cars on the road, people are putting extreme loads on the power grid. 

üá∫üá∏ Timed Meter!
In Bay Area, California where I live. I charge my car only during the night. Because electricity is very very expensive during day time! 
Yes, there is a timed meter at my home. 
I have programmed to charge my Tesla only after 12midnight.
I will plug it in during the day, but it will start charging only after 12 midnight. 

üáÆüá≥In India, where the new powerlines are laid under the ground. 
üá∫üá∏But in the USA, so many homes have overhead power cables. 

üá∫üá∏Long Ago
Since the USA started creating electricity lines so long ago. They did not think through a good solution. They laid miles and miles of overhead power lines, which is susceptible to extreme weather conditions. 

üá∫üá∏Climate Change
With increasing extreme weather conditions all around the USA, the cables are falling down. 

üá∫üá∏Labor
Furthermore,  Labor is very expensive in the USA. Government and Utility contractors could not finish their jobs on time due to a lack of skilled labor. 

üá∫üá∏Immigration:
The country's leaders are refusing to make a comprehensive immigration change. This condition is only going to get worse. The USA lacks the know-how, skills, and physical labor to fix the infrastructure. 

This is my opinion only. Please do your own research.

Recent investigations have revealed that two of Italy's most prominent luxury fashion houses, Dior and Giorgio Armani, pay a surprisingly low amount to produce handbags that retail for thousands of dollars. Documents examined by the authorities show that Dior paid a supplier only $57 to make bags that sell for about $2,780. So, what explains this stupendous price markup? Are you paying for quality handbags or are you paying for the brand? Palki Sharma answers the questions.

India has had a long, colourful, and mixed history with Liquor over the centuries, with ancient fermented drinks and traditional liquors like feni and toddy. India today, holds the third-largest market for alcoholic beverages globally, which is remarkable given the challenging business environment of red tape-ism, varying excise duties across states and much more.
In episode #18 of ‚ÄúWTF is‚Äù Podcast, we have Founders of different sectors in the Liquor Industry of India. Abhishek Khaitan, MD of Radico Khaitan, One of the oldest and largest manufacturers of Indian Made Foreign Liquor (IMFL) in India; Minakshi Singh, Co-founder of SideCar, India‚Äôs only entry in the top 100 of the World‚Äôs Best Bars; Shuchir Suri, Co founder of Gin Explorer‚Äôs Club, India‚Äôs biggest gin festival with a footfall of over 100,000 people per edition; and Suraj Shenai, Founder of Goa Brewing Co, crafting ‚Äònon-conformist, modern‚Äô beers that challenge the traditional dominance of German and Belgian flavours.

If Euphemism for patriotism is outrightly sold to people, across the world in different pockets, can the same brand-building tactics work for Indian Products too?

liked_videos.title: How Distributed Lock works | ft Redis | System Design
liked_videos.description:
Distributed locking is a key concept in ensuring data integrity and consistency in distributed systems. In this video we explore distributed locking mechanisms including centralized locking, token-based locking, and quorum-based locking, explaining their principles, advantages, and limitations.

We then look into Redis based Redlock, a widely adopted quorum-based locking algorithm that provides high availability and fault tolerance. We break down the Redlock algorithm step by step, highlighting how it leverages multiple Redis instances to achieve consensus on lock acquisition.

Throughout the video, I emphasize the importance of distributed locking in maintaining data integrity and preventing conflicts in concurrent systems. 

We also discuss real-world applications of distributed locking, such as managing inventory in e-commerce systems and coordinating access to shared resources in cloud environments.

liked_videos.title: Population of the USA üá∫üá∏ Why 80% of Americans Live East of This Line?
liked_videos.description:
Have you ever wondered why a significant majority of Americans reside east of a particular line, while only a smaller fraction occupies the western part of the United States? üá∫üá∏ Uncover the geographic factors that contribute to this fascinating phenomenon. Discover how the majority of western residents are concentrated in California, Oregon, and Washington within this line, accounting for a significant portion of the region's population. Furthermore, explore the astonishing statistic that only 9% of Americans live in half of the mainland US, equivalent to the population of New York City alone. üò± Learn about the primary reason behind this geographical distribution: the imposing Rocky Mountains, which serve as a natural barrier to Pacific Ocean rains, creating a phenomenon known as the "rain shadow." Delve into how these mountains hinder cloud movement, impacting precipitation patterns across the country. Explore the intricate interplay between precipitation patterns and wind currents, particularly the influence of Gulf of Mexico winds along the 100th meridian. Understand how these factors contribute to the creation of dry, agriculturally unsuitable regions and their subsequent impact on population density.
The journey through America's diverse geography and uncover the complex dynamics that shape where Americans choose to call home.

When they ran to save their lives for the first time, they were mere 12-year-old boys, and the world called them 'refugees'.

The war of 1971 gave birth to a new country - Bangladesh. It also gave birth to two young orphans - Bikram and Bala. They witnessed the war and its aftermath, where the world tried to trample over them. Fighting for survival, they clung to each other and escaped to Calcutta.

Before they knew the world, they knew each other. Such was their bond, such was their friendship.

Each time they sought new beginnings, each time they would rise, the world would crush them down. So, they fought again... and again. Together they were unbeatable. They were unstoppable. They were inseparable.

In the years that passed, Bikram and Bala, became Calcutta's most loved, most celebrated, most reckless, most fearless and most powerful GUNDAY!

They had everything... then, one fine day, bells rang...

Nandita, the most beautiful cabaret dancer, walked into their lives, and they lost everything to her. Their murky world turned magical and colourful. They fell head over heels in love with her.

But that was only a blissful lull before an impending storm...

And then entered ACP Satyajeet Sarkar, the right for every wrong, a law for every outlaw and a counter force for Bikram and Bala.

What follows from here is the most sensational-most thrilling-most dramatic story ever told!

liked_videos.title: What is a GPU vs a CPU? [And why GPUs are used for Machine Learning]
liked_videos.description:
What is a GPU and how is it different than a GPU? GPUs and CPUs are both silicone based microprocessors but they differ in what they specialize in. GPUs specialize in parallel computations, and CPUs specialize in serial computations. 
While GPUs are known for a key component of getting the great graphics you want in your gamming, they are also known in the Machine Learning and AI Community for helping crunch millions of parameters needed to train a machine.
Learn more in this episode of GLITCH.

liked_videos.title: How to pick a Mutual Fund?
liked_videos.description:
Many people look at returns while selecting a mutual fund. However, return is not the only parameter to choose a mutual fund. Selecting an investment is never so easy. You should look at performance, risk, and cost metrics while selecting a mutual fund.

This video talks about the following 6 metrics one should check while selecting a mutual fund:
- Rolling Returns
- Sharpe Ratio
- Standard Deviation
- Beta
- Asset Under Management (AUM)
- Total Expense Ratio (TER)

Also, you can find below a mutual fund fitness scorecard which acts as a checklist for you while selecting a suitable mutual fund for your portfolio.

liked_videos.title: The Rise of India as a Global Economic Power | Bloomberg Originals Marathon
liked_videos.description:
A collection of India-centric documentaries covering its fast-growing economy, China relations, religious tensions, the rise of Narendra Modi and industry deep dives. 

0:00 - How India Can Win China's Growth Crown
7:29 - How Narendra Modi Took Power in India
30:34 - What This $200 Million Temple Says About Modi‚Äôs India
40:08 - Inside Luxury‚Äôs Secret India Supply Chain
48:08 - How India's Drug Exports May Have a Safety Problem
57:12 - Inside Modi's Dangerous Bet on Alternative Medicine
1:04:12 - India‚Äôs Obesity Time Bomb 

How India Can Win China's Growth Crown: https://youtu.be/Q6q8TI2oUmc Originally published April 5, 2024

China‚Äôs economy is slowing and India is vying to take its place as the world‚Äôs biggest driver of growth. But the path is filled with obstacles. What does India need to fix before it can take China‚Äôs crown? 

Read the full story: https://trib.al/Ubb7SZX

How Narendra Modi Took Power in India: https://youtu.be/FLQoCNzoT2o Originally published May 15, 2024

Narendra Modi, India‚Äôs 73-year-old prime minister, is both highly popular and deeply polarizing. How did he work his way to the top of Indian politics, and what do his policies mean for the country‚Äôs future, both at home and on the world stage?

Bloomberg Originals speaks with childhood friends, government officials and former associates who have seen Modi up close over the years, seeking to understand how his core beliefs may have shaped his decision-making. We also show how he has sought to simultaneously make himself a champion of the poor and a friend to billionaires.

Sitting at the top of the world‚Äôs most populous nation and one of its fastest growing economies, Modi occupies a uniquely important and powerful position in geopolitics, global trade and finance ‚Äì especially as China‚Äôs growth has slowed. We explain how he got there, and what may come next.

Read more about How Narendra Modi Is Preparing for a Thousand-Year Legacy on Bloomberg: https://www.bloomberg.com/features/2024-modi-legacy-india-elections/

What This $200 Million Temple Says About Modi‚Äôs India: https://youtu.be/Dfxtx1Y0T9E Originally published January 19, 2024

When Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi inaugurates the new Hindu temple in Ayodhya, many will see it as the capstone of his 10 years in power. Built on the site of a former mosque at a cost estimated at more than $200 million, the temple shows how his Bharatiya Janata Party has become a seemingly unstoppable electoral machine. And the timing of the inauguration, just months before national elections, may boost the election prospects of Modi and his fellow Hindu nationalists. 

Inside Luxury‚Äôs Secret India Supply Chain: https://youtu.be/Qy2JWUOwTWQ Originally published September 28, 2023

Some of your ‚ÄúMade in France‚Äù luxury items are actually made in India. For decades, fashion houses obscured their business ties to developing nations where labor is cheap, and hard-to-find handicraft skills plentiful.

Today, credit sharing remains contested, even as laws tighten around transparency. We set out to investigate what‚Äôs behind a garment label.

How India's Drug Exports May Have a Safety Problem: https://youtu.be/3BoQsnqC5zM Originally published December 15, 2023

Hospitals around the world use drugs from a small but crucial Indian supplier. In Colombia four kids died and more than a hundred fell ill. In a months-long investigation, Bloomberg Businessweek found that, despite a track record of safety lapses and quality concerns, the manufacturer continued selling its drugs. 

Read the full story: http://www.trib.al/NPh1C4F

Inside Modi's Dangerous Bet on Alternative Medicine: https://youtu.be/msJOeyHQOoQ Originally published February 28, 2024

India‚Äôs alternative medicine industry is booming as ancient principles of healthy living gain new traction, thanks in part to support from Narendra Modi‚Äôs government.  ‚ÄúAyurveda‚Äù, an ancient medical system that has existed in India for centuries, is flourishing with help from holistic-living influencers with vast reach on Instagram and YouTube. But there's a dark side to Ayurveda‚Äôs popularity.

Some doctors in India are seeing patients suffer serious injuries from long term use of ayurvedic medicines. Medical professionals trying to raise awareness about the dangers of alternative medicines have faced lawsuits and even government intervention.

India‚Äôs Obesity Time Bomb: https://youtu.be/VLZXmSToMi8 Originally published November 3, 2023

Almost 1 in 4 adults is considered overweight or obese in India. As junk food giants push into developing nations with weaker public health awareness, campaigners are calling for tougher regulation.

liked_videos.title: All You Need to Know about BUY NOW PAY LATER | Ep. #17 ft. Axio
liked_videos.description:
Axio, formerly known as Capital Float, is India's leading BNPL, NBFC, and credit platform, designed to meet the financial needs of both salaried and self-employed individuals across the country. Founded by Sashank Rishyasringa and Gaurav Hinduja in 2013, Axio offers core products including Buy Now Pay Later, personal loans, and an app for tracking finances. Leveraging advanced technology, they serve around 9 million customers, process 7 million loans a month, and generate a revenue of 8000 crores annually.

Backed by marquee investors like Elevation Capital (formerly SAIF Partners), Sequoia India, Lightrock, Creation Investments Capital Management LLC, Ribbit Capital, and Amazon, Axio is committed to revolutionizing financial accessibility in India.

The Off Campus team visited their office in Bangalore and met with the founders and their team to gain insights into the business behind running a digital credit company.

For more content like this, subscribe to our channel @mastersunion.

liked_videos.title: How Compounding Works? Problem with Stocks & Mutual Funds
liked_videos.description:
Compounding is a phenomenon that works wonders over time. It's like a snowball rolling down a hill, gathering more snow and growing larger as it goes. At its core, compounding involves earning returns on both the original investment and the returns that have already been generated. This creates a snowball effect where wealth accumulates exponentially over time.

Here's how it works: let's say you invest Rs. 1000 in a stock or mutual fund that earns an annual return of 10%. In the first year, you earn Rs. 100 in returns, bringing your total investment to Rs. 1100. In the second year, you earn 10% on the entire Rs. 1100, not just the original Rs. 1000. This means you earn Rs. 110 in returns, bringing your total investment to Rs. 1210.

As the years go by, this process repeats itself, with your investment growing larger and larger with each passing year. The longer you leave your money invested, the more powerful compounding becomes. Over time, even small, regular investments can grow into significant sums.

Compounding is often referred to as the "eighth wonder of the world" because of its remarkable ability to grow wealth over time. However, it's important to remember that compounding works best over long periods. It requires patience and discipline to let your investments grow and resist the temptation to withdraw your money prematurely.

By harnessing the power of compounding and staying invested for the long term, you can build wealth steadily and achieve your financial goals. So start early, invest regularly, and let the power of compounding work its magic for you.

Compounding isn't just about finances; it's a principle applicable to life's many facets. Small, consistent efforts, like daily exercise, can compound into significant improvements in health. Similarly, acts of kindness in relationships build trust over time. Skill-building, with just 15 minutes of practice daily, leads to expertise. This universal principle underscores the power of consistency in achieving incremental gains. So, whether in finances or personal growth, embrace the compounding effect, and watch as steady efforts yield remarkable results across all areas of life.

liked_videos.title: DynamoDB Partition Key: 5 Things You Must Know Before It's Too Late (AWS)
liked_videos.description:
Choosing the right partition key is crucial to achieving good performance and scalability in DynamoDB. 

Hi Guys, this is Abi from Gokce DB and in this video, you are going to learn 5 things that you should know before choosing a partition key.

1. A good partition key should have high cardinality, meaning that it should have a large number of distinct values. This ensures that the data is evenly distributed across the partitions, which results in better performance and scalability. Examples include emailid, employee_no, customerid, sessionid & orderid.

2. Choose a partition key that will be frequently queried. The partition key is used to retrieve data from DynamoDB, so it should be chosen based on the most common queries that will be performed. If a partition key is rarely queried, it will result in uneven distribution of data and may lead to hot partitions, which can cause performance issues.

3. Avoid using always increasing values as partition keys such as a timestamps. This can cause all new data to be written to the same partition, resulting in a hot partition. As mentioned earlier, uneven distribution of data can impact the performance of the database.

4. Consider using composite partition keys which means you should try to combine more than one attribute to form a unique key. For example, you could use a combination of customer ID, product ID and country code as a composite partition key if that meets your access pattern.

5. Cache popular items when there is a high volume of read traffic using Amazon DynamoDB Accelerator or DAX.  It is a fully managed, in-memory cache for DynamoDB that will prevent reads of unusually popular items from swamping partitions.

Remember, you cannot change partition key after the table is created. 
By following these best practices, you can choose a partition key that will optimize performance and scalability in Amazon DynamoDB.

liked_videos.title: Capacity Planning and Estimation: How much data does YouTube store daily?
liked_videos.description:
Back-of-the-envelope calculations are often expected in system design questions. They help logically state the parameters influencing a result, and estimating the capacity requires multiple estimations on the way. Also lets us individually state our assumptions.

Eg: Estimate the hardware requirements to set up a system like YouTube.
Eg: Estimate the number of petrol pumps in the city of Mumbai.

Chapters
00:06 Storage Requirements
01:20 Supplementary storage requirements
03:54 Back of Envelope calculations
05:38 Youtube caching estimation
08:58 Youtube video processing estimation
12:14 Conclusion

------STORAGE
Let's start with storage requirements:
About 1 billion active users.
I assume 1/1000 produces a video a day.
Which means 1 million new videos a day.

What's the size of each video?
Assume the average length of a video to be 10 minutes. 
 Assume a 10 minute video to be of size 1 GB. Or...
A video is a bunch of images. 10 minutes is 600 seconds. Each second has 24 frames. So a video has 25*600 = 150,000 frames.
 Each frame is of size 1 MB. Which means (1.5 * 10^5) * (10^6) bytes = 150 GB.
This estimate is very inaccurate, and hence we must either revise our estimate or hope the interviewer corrects us. Normal video of 10 minutes is about 700 MB.

As each video is of about 1GB, we assume the storage requirement per day is 1GB * 1 million = 1 PB. 

This is the bare minimum storage requirement to store the original videos. If we want to have redundancy for fault tolerance and performance, we have to store copies. I'll choose 3 copies. 
That's 3 petabytes of raw data storage.
What about video formats and encoding? Let's assume a single type of encoding, mp4, and the formats will take a 720p video and store it in 480, 360, 240 and 144p respectively. That means approximately half the video size per codec.

If X is the original storage requirement = 1 PB,
We have X + X/2 + X/4 + X/8 == 2*X.
With redundancy, that's 2X * 3 = 6*X.

That's 6 PB(processed) + 3PB (raw)  == 10 PB of data. About 100 hard drives. The cost of this system is about 1 million per day.

For a 3 year plan, we can expect a 1 billion dollar storage price.

Now let's look at the real numbers:
Video upload speed = 3 * 10^4 minutes per minute.
That's 3 * 10^4 *1440 video footage per day =  4.5 * 10^7 minutes.
Video encoding can reduce a 1-hour film to 1 GB. So 1 million GB is the requirement. That's 1 PB.

So the original cost is similar to what the real numbers say.


If we are off by order of magnitude, it's good. However, being off by 3 or more orders of magnitude is too much. We can then highlight the following:
Where our assumption was wrong, or 
Which factor we didn't take into account.

Sign up and get 40% off - https://app.codecrafters.io/join?via=arpitbbhayani

In the video, I dissected the Google File System research paper from 2003, highlighting its key aspects. The system is designed to run on commodity hardware, making it scalable and fault-tolerant. Google optimized for storing large files, focusing on append operations rather than overwrites. They also emphasized fault detection, fault tolerance, and automated recovery. The system divided files into chunks for parallelism, load balancing, fault tolerance, and easy storage allocation. Replication factor of 3 ensured fault tolerance, with a master node managing metadata.
